<|asst|>
Tom and Sue were playing in the yard. They saw a big pile of leaves. They wanted to jump in it and have fun.

"Let's go, Tom!" Sue said. "The leaves are so soft and colorful!"

But Tom saw something else. He saw a rake next to the pile. He knew that Dad had worked hard to rake the leaves. He also knew that Dad did not like it when they messed up his work.

"Wait, Sue," Tom said. "We should not jump in the leaves. Dad will be mad. He will have to rake them again."

Sue did not listen. She ran to the pile and jumped in. She laughed and threw leaves in the air. Tom felt bad. He did not want to make Dad mad. He did not want to join Sue.

Sue saw that Tom was not happy. She stopped laughing. She looked at Tom.

"Why are you not playing, Tom?" Sue asked. "Don't you like the leaves?"

Tom shook his head. He pointed at the rake.

"Dad raked the leaves," Tom said. "He worked hard. He will be mad if we mess them up. We should cover them back."

Sue looked at the rake. She looked at the leaves. She felt sorry. She did not think about Dad. She only thought about herself.

"You are right, Tom," Sue said. "I was wrong. I was selfish. I did not think about Dad. I am sorry. Let's cover the leaves back."

Tom smiled. He was glad that Sue understood. They worked together to cover the leaves back. They used the rake to make the pile neat. They felt good. They did the right thing.

Dad came out of the house. He saw the pile of leaves. He saw Tom and Sue. He smiled.

"Thank you, Tom and Sue," Dad said. "You did a good job. You helped me. You were kind and respectful. I am proud of you."

Tom and Sue hugged Dad. They were happy. They learned a lesson. They learned to think about others. They learned to be responsible. They learned to be good.
<|end|>


