<|asst|>
Lily and Ben liked to play in the park. They liked to run, jump, slide and swing. They also liked to look for things in the grass and under the trees. One day, they found a big oak. It had many branches and leaves. It was very old and strong.

They decided to climb the oak. They used their hands and feet to go up and up. They felt very brave and happy. They saw birds, squirrels and bugs on the oak. They also saw the whole park and the sky. They waved to their mom, who was sitting on a bench.

But then, they heard a loud noise. It was a big truck. It came to the park. It had a long arm with a saw. It stopped near the oak. The man in the truck got out. He put on a helmet and gloves. He looked at the oak. He said, "This oak is too old and sick. It might fall and hurt someone. I have to cut it down."

Lily and Ben were scared and sad. They liked the oak. They did not want it to go. They shouted, "Stop! Stop! Don't cut the oak! It is our friend! It is useful! It gives us shade and fun and homes for animals! Please, stop!"

The man heard them. He looked up and saw them on the oak. He was surprised and worried. He said, "Hey, kids, what are you doing up there? You have to come down. It is not safe. I have to do my job."

Lily and Ben did not want to come down. They hugged the oak. They said, "No, no, we won't come down. We love the oak. We want to save it. Please, don't cut it. Please, please, please."

The man did not know what to do. He called their mom. She came and saw them on the oak. She was also surprised and worried. She said, "Lily, Ben, listen to me. You have to come down. The man is right. The oak is old and sick. It might fall and hurt you or someone else. It is not your fault. It is not his fault. It is just how things are. Sometimes, we have to say goodbye to things we love. But we can always remember them and be thankful for them. Please, come down. I will help you."

Lily and Ben looked at their mom. They looked at the man. They looked at the oak. They felt very sad. But they also knew their mom was right. They slowly came down from the oak. They said, "We are sorry, oak. We will miss you. Thank you for everything. Goodbye, oak."

The man said, "Thank you, kids. You are very brave and kind. I am sorry, too. I don't like to cut trees. But sometimes, I have to. I will try to be gentle and quick. I will also plant a new tree here. Maybe, one day, you can come back and play with it."

Lily and Ben nodded. They hugged their mom. They watched the man cut the oak. They cried a little. But they also smiled a little. They knew the oak had a good life. They knew they had a good memory. They knew they had a good mom. They knew they had each other. They knew they would be okay.
<|end|>


