Lily was restless. She did not want to sleep. She wanted to play with her toys and read her books. But Mommy said it was bedtime and turned off the light.

"Please, Mommy, can I have a story?" Lily asked.

"Okay, one story, but then you have to sleep," Mommy said. She picked up a book from the shelf and opened it. "This is a story about a fairy who lived in a garden."

Lily loved fairies. She listened to Mommy's voice as she read the story. The fairy had wings and a wand and could do magic. She helped the flowers grow and the animals be happy. She was kind and brave and smart.

But one day, the fairy realized she was lonely. She had no friends like her. She wished she could find another fairy to play with and talk to. She flew around the garden, looking for a sign of another fairy.

Lily felt sad for the fairy. She wanted her to find a friend. She wondered if there were any fairies in her own garden. She wished she could see one.

"Mommy, do you think there are fairies in our garden?" Lily asked.

Mommy smiled and closed the book. "Maybe there are, maybe there aren't. You never know. But if you want to see a fairy, you have to believe in them and be very quiet and still. Maybe they will come to you in your dreams."

Lily nodded. She decided to try to see a fairy in her dreams. She closed her eyes and imagined a fairy flying to her window. She whispered, "Hello, fairy. Do you want to be my friend?"

She did not hear an answer, but she felt a warm breeze and a soft touch on her cheek. She smiled and fell asleep.
