Ben and Sam were brothers. They liked to play with their toys. One day, they saw a man with a big truck. The man had many toys in his truck. He said he would sell them for cheap.

Ben and Sam ran to the man. They wanted to buy some toys. They had some money from their piggy bank. They looked at the toys. They saw cars, dolls, balls, and puzzles. They also saw a green box. The box was dull and had no picture on it.

"What is in the green box?" Ben asked the man.

"It is a surprise toy. It is very fun and special. You can have it for only one dollar," the man said.

Ben and Sam were curious. They wanted to see the surprise toy. They gave the man one dollar and took the green box. They ran back to their house. They opened the box.

But there was no toy in the box. There was only a rock. A dull, gray rock. Ben and Sam were sad and angry. They had wasted their money. They had no new toy. They had been tricked by the man.

They tried to find the man and his truck. But he was gone. He had driven away with his toys and their money. Ben and Sam cried. They wished they had not bought the green box. They wished they had bought a car or a doll or a ball or a puzzle instead. They learned a hard lesson. They learned to be careful and not trust strangers. They learned to not judge a book by its cover. Or a box by its color.
<|end|>


