<|asst|>
Sara and her mom went to the park. Sara liked to play on the swings and the slide. Her mom sat on a bench and watched her. She had a big purse with snacks and water.

"Mom, can I have some water?" Sara asked. She was thirsty from running and jumping.

"Sure, honey. Come here and I'll give you some." Her mom opened her purse and took out a bottle of water.

Sara ran to her mom and stretched her arms to reach the bottle. But she was too short. She tried to jump, but she still could not get it.

"Here, let me help you." Her mom lifted Sara up and gave her the bottle. Sara drank some water and said, "Thank you, mom. You are the best."

"You're welcome, sweetie. Be careful, don't spill the water." Her mom said.

Sara nodded and ran back to the playground. She wanted to go on the slide again. But when she got there, she saw that the slide was wet. Someone had poured water on it. It looked slippery and shiny.

"Who did this?" Sara wondered. She saw a boy with a bucket near the slide. He was laughing and splashing water on the slide.

"Hey, stop that!" Sara shouted. "You are making the slide wet. That's not nice."

The boy looked at Sara and said, "So what? It's fun. You can slide faster when it's wet. Watch me." He climbed up the slide and slid down. He went very fast and landed on the grass.

Sara did not think it was fun. She thought it was dangerous and rude. She did not want to slide on the wet slide. She wanted to tell her mom. She ran to the bench where her mom was. But when she got there, she saw that her mom's purse was wet too. The boy had splashed water on it when he slid down.

"Oh no!" Sara cried. "Mom, look! Your purse is wet. The boy did it. He made the slide wet too. He is a bad boy."

Her mom looked at her purse and frowned. She saw that her snacks and water were wet and soggy. She was not happy. She said, "That's not nice at all. He should not do that. Let's go and talk to him. Maybe he will say sorry and stop."

Sara and her mom went to the slide and found the boy. They told him that he was wrong to splash water on the slide and the purse. They asked him to say sorry and stop.

The boy looked at them and said, "Sorry. I was just having fun. I didn't mean to make you mad. I won't do it again."

Sara and her mom accepted his apology and thanked him. They hoped he would be more careful and respectful next time. They decided to go to another part of the park where it was dry and clean. They had fun playing together and forgot about the wet slide and the wet purse.
<|end|>


