<|asst|>
Sara and Tom were brother and sister. They liked to play in the park with their ball and their bike. One day, they saw a tall man in the park. He had a big bag and a thermometer in his hand. He looked at the trees and the flowers with the thermometer.

"Hello, what are you doing?" Sara asked the tall man.

"I am a scientist. I am measuring how hot or cold the plants are. Do you want to see?" the tall man said.

"Yes, please!" Tom said. He liked to learn new things.

The tall man showed them how the thermometer worked. He put it on a leaf and said, "This leaf is 20 degrees. That means it is warm, but not too hot." He put it on a flower and said, "This flower is 15 degrees. That means it is cooler than the leaf." He put it on a rock and said, "This rock is 10 degrees. That means it is cold and hard."

Sara and Tom were amazed. They asked the tall man many questions. He answered them kindly. He told them that plants need the right temperature to grow and be healthy. He also told them that people need the right temperature to be well and happy.

"Thank you for teaching us, Mr. Scientist. You are very smart and nice," Sara said.

"You are welcome, Sara and Tom. You are very curious and polite," the tall man said. "But remember, you should not touch the thermometer without asking. It is a tool, not a toy. It can break or hurt you if you are not careful."

Sara and Tom nodded. They understood. They said goodbye to the tall man and went back to their ball and their bike. They had fun in the park, but they also learned something new. They were glad they met the tall man with the thermometer.
<|end|>


