<|end|>
<|asst|>
Ben was a boy who liked to dress up in costumes. He had a pirate costume, a superhero costume, a dinosaur costume and many more. He liked to pretend he was different characters and have fun. But he had a problem. He had no friends to play with. He was lonely.

One day, he saw a poster on the wall of his school. It said: "Costume Party! Come and join us for games, snacks and prizes! Friday at 3 pm in the gym." Ben was very excited. He thought: "This is my chance to make friends! I can show them my costumes and have fun with them!"

He ran home and told his mom. She said: "That sounds great, Ben! What costume do you want to wear?" Ben thought for a while. He wanted to wear his best costume, the one that would impress everyone. He said: "I want to wear my robot costume! It has lights and sounds and it looks very cool!"

His mom said: "OK, Ben, but remember, it's not the costume that makes you a good friend. It's your kindness, your honesty and your sharing. Don't forget that."

Ben nodded, but he didn't listen. He thought his mom didn't understand. He thought his costume would make everyone like him.

On Friday, he put on his robot costume and went to the party. He walked into the gym and saw many kids in different costumes. He saw a princess, a cowboy, a clown, a fairy and more. He thought: "Wow, they look nice, but my costume is better!"

He walked around the gym, making loud noises and flashing his lights. He wanted everyone to notice him and admire him. But he didn't talk to anyone. He didn't ask them their names, or what they liked, or if they wanted to play. He just showed off his costume.

Soon, he realized that no one was paying attention to him. They were busy playing games, eating snacks and having fun. They were talking and laughing with each other. They were making friends. Ben felt sad. He felt lonely. He wished he had listened to his mom.

He saw a girl in a simple costume. She was wearing a yellow dress and a sunflower on her head. She was smiling and waving at him. She said: "Hi, I'm Lily. I like your costume. It's very shiny. Do you want to play with me?"

Ben felt a warm feeling in his heart. He smiled and said: "Hi, I'm Ben. Thank you. I like your costume too. It's very pretty. Yes, I want to play with you."

He took off his robot helmet and held her hand. They went to join the other kids. They played games, ate snacks and had fun. They talked and laughed with each other. They made friends. Ben felt happy. He was not lonely anymore.

He learned a lesson that day. He learned that it's not the costume that makes you a good friend. It's your kindness, your honesty and your sharing. He learned that being yourself is the best way to make friends. He learned that his mom was right.
<|end|>


