Tom is a big boy who goes to school. He likes to draw and write on his desk. He has many colors and pencils in his box. He makes pictures of his family, his friends and his toys.

One day, his teacher is very busy. She has to check many papers and talk to many people. She does not see what Tom is doing. Tom draws a big sun on his desk with a yellow crayon. He thinks it is pretty.

"Look, teacher, I made a sun!" Tom says, showing his desk.

The teacher turns around and sees the sun. She is not happy. She frowns and says, "Tom, you should not draw on your desk. That is not good. You have to rub it off with a cloth. Now!"

Tom feels sad. He does not want to rub off his sun. He likes his sun. He says, "But teacher, it is a nice sun. It makes me happy. Can I keep it, please?"

The teacher shakes her head and says, "No, Tom, you cannot keep it. You have to rub it off. It is not your desk. It is the school's desk. You have to keep it clean and tidy. Come on, rub it off now."

Tom sighs and takes a cloth. He rubs his sun slowly and softly. He does not want to say goodbye to his sun. He wishes he could keep it. He thinks the teacher is not nice. He thinks the desk is boring. He rubs and rubs until the sun is gone. He feels sad. He does not want to draw anymore. He puts his crayon back in his box. He looks at his desk. It is clean and tidy. But it is not pretty.
<|end|>


