Sara liked to dig in the dirt. She liked to find worms and put them in a jar. She wanted to keep them as pets. She thought they were cute and wiggly.

One day, she found a big, fat worm. It was the biggest worm she ever saw. She was very happy. She put it in her jar with the other worms. She ran to show her mom.

"Look, mom, look! I found a big worm!" she said.

Mom looked at the jar. She saw the big worm. She also saw something else. She looked scared.

"Sara, that's not a worm. That's a snake!" she said.

Sara looked at the jar again. She saw the big worm had a head and a tail. It had eyes and a mouth. It was not a worm. It was a snake. A loud snake. It hissed and rattled. It was angry.

Sara dropped the jar. The jar broke. The snake came out. It slithered away. The other worms came out too. They crawled away. Sara was sad. She lost her worms. She lost her jar. She was scared of the snake.

She regretted picking up the big worm. She wished she had left it alone. She learned a lesson. Not all worms are the same. Some worms are snakes. Snakes are not pets. Snakes are dangerous.
