Lily and Ben were playing pirates in the garden. They had a big box full of gold coins that they pretended to find in a treasure chest. They also had a blue flag with a skull and bones on it that they waved in the air.

"Arrr, we are the best pirates in the world!" Ben shouted. "No one can take our gold from us!"

But then they saw Tom, the boy next door, peeking over the fence. He had a red hat and a wooden sword. He wanted to play with them, but they did not like him. He was always mean and bossy.

"Hey, you two, give me some of your gold!" Tom said. "Or I will attack you with my sword!"

"No, go away, Tom!" Lily said. "This is our gold, we found it fair and square!"

"Yeah, you can't have any, Tom!" Ben said. "You are not a pirate, you are a landlubber!"

Tom was angry. He jumped over the fence and ran towards them. He tried to grab the box of gold, but Lily and Ben held on to it. They pulled and tugged, but none of them would let go.

"Stop it, Tom, you are hurting us!" Lily cried.

"Pay me some gold, or I will hurt you more!" Tom said.

They were all shouting and fighting, when they heard a loud voice.

"What is going on here?" It was Lily's mom. She had heard the noise and came to see what was wrong. She saw the three children wrestling over the box of gold. She was not happy.

"Tom, you go back to your house right now!" she said. "You have no right to take their gold or to hurt them!"

"But they won't share with me!" Tom whined.

"That's because it's their gold, not yours!" she said. "You have to ask nicely and say please and thank you, not demand and threaten!"

She took the box of gold from them and gave it back to Lily and Ben. She also took the blue flag and the wooden sword and put them away.

"Come on, Lily and Ben, let's go inside and have some juice and cookies," she said. "You can play pirates again later, but only with nice friends."

Lily and Ben followed their mom, happy to have their gold back. They did not look at Tom, who was still standing by the fence, feeling sorry for himself. He wished he had been nicer to them, and maybe they would have let him play. But he did not know how to say sorry. He did not know how to be a good friend.
<|end|>


