Sara and Tom are friends. They like to play in the park. One day, they see a big bird. The bird has a nest. The nest has eggs.

"Look, eggs!" Sara says. "Can we see them?"

"No, no," Tom says. "We must not touch them. The bird will be mad. The eggs are her work. She takes care of them."

"But I want to see them," Sara says. "They are so pretty. Maybe they have baby birds inside."

Sara goes to the nest. She reaches for an egg. The bird sees her. The bird is mad. She flies to Sara. She pecks at her hand.

"Ow, ow!" Sara cries. "The bird hurts me!"

Tom runs to Sara. He helps her. He takes her hand. He says, "I'm sorry, Sara. Are you fine?"

Sara looks at her hand. It has a red mark. It hurts a little. She says, "I'm fine, Tom. Thank you. You are a good friend."

The bird goes back to the nest. She checks her eggs. They are fine. She is happy.

Sara and Tom go back to the park. They play with other things. They do not touch the eggs again. They learn to respect the bird's work.
<|end|>


