Lily and Ben were at the park with their mom. They saw a big fountain with water that went up and down. Lily wanted to play in the fountain, but Ben said no.

"Mom said we can't get wet, Lily. It's too cold today. You are stupid if you go in the fountain," Ben said.

Lily did not like Ben calling her stupid. She was not stupid. She was brave and fun. She ran to the fountain and put her hand in the water. It was cold, but it felt nice. She laughed and splashed.

"Stop it, Lily! You are making a mess! Mom will be mad at you!" Ben shouted. He ran after Lily and tried to pull her away from the fountain. Lily did not want to go. She pinched Ben's arm hard.

"Ow! That hurts, Lily! You are mean!" Ben cried. He pinched Lily back.

"Ow! Stop it, Ben! You are meaner!" Lily cried. They both pinched each other and cried louder and louder.

Mom heard them and came to see what was wrong. She saw them wet and pinching and crying. She was not happy.

"What are you doing, Lily and Ben? Why are you fighting and pinching and getting wet? You know the rules. No playing in the fountain. No hurting each other. You are both in trouble. Come with me right now," Mom said.

Lily and Ben felt sorry. They stopped pinching and crying. They followed Mom to the car. They said sorry to each other and to Mom. Mom said she loved them, but they had to behave better. They nodded and hugged Mom. They learned their lesson. Pinching was not nice. Playing in the fountain was not smart. Listening to Mom was the best.
<|end|>


