<|asst|>
Lily and Ben love chocolate. They have a big box of chocolate that their mom gave them. They want to share the chocolate, but they do not know how. They need to number the chocolate.

Lily says, "I can number the chocolate. I am powerful. I know one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten."

Ben says, "No, I can number the chocolate. I am powerful too. I know one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten, eleven, twelve."

Lily and Ben start to fight. They pull the chocolate. They yell at each other. They make a big mess.

Mom hears the noise. She comes to the room. She sees the chocolate on the floor. She sees Lily and Ben crying.

Mom says, "Stop, stop, stop. What are you doing? Why are you fighting?"

Lily and Ben say, "We want to share the chocolate, but we do not know how. We both can number the chocolate. We both are powerful."

Mom says, "I am sorry, but you are not powerful. You are silly. You do not need to number the chocolate. You just need to split the chocolate. You can each have half of the chocolate. That is fair. That is easy. That is nice."

Lily and Ben say, "Oh, we are sorry, mom. We did not think of that. We will split the chocolate. We will be fair. We will be easy. We will be nice."

Mom says, "Good. I am glad. Now, pick up the chocolate. Put it in the box. Then, you can have some chocolate. But not too much. Chocolate is a treat. You need to eat other food too."

Lily and Ben say, "OK, mom. Thank you, mom. We love you, mom. We love chocolate too. But we love you more."
<|end|>


