Ben and Lily went to the park with Mom. They saw many things to play with: swings, slides, sand, and a big pond. But Ben and Lily liked the statues best. They were big and funny and made of stone.

"Look, Lily, this statue is a jolly man with a big hat and a beard. He is holding a book. What do you think he is reading?" Ben asked.

"Maybe he is reading a story. I like stories. Can you read it to me, Ben?" Lily said.

"I can't read it, Lily. It has big words that I don't know. But we can count the words. Do you know how to count?" Ben said.

"Yes, I do. I can count to ten. Watch me. One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten. I did it!" Lily said.

"Good job, Lily. You are very smart. Let's count the words on the book. One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten, eleven, twelve. There are twelve words on the book. That's more than ten. Can you say twelve?" Ben said.

"Twelve. That's a hard word. But I can say it. Twelve. Twelve. Twelve." Lily said.

Mom came over and smiled. She was proud of Ben and Lily. They were learning new things and having fun.

"Are you enjoying the statues, kids? They are very old and interesting. Do you want to know more about them?" Mom said.

"Yes, please, Mom. Tell us more. We like the statues. They are jolly and nice." Ben and Lily said.
<|end|>


