Ben and Lily were twins who liked to play games. One day, they found a big box in the attic. Inside the box, there were many pieces of wood with different shapes and colors. They looked like little people and animals.

"What is this?" Ben asked.

"I don't know. Maybe it's a puzzle," Lily said.

They took out the pieces and tried to fit them together on a board with black and white squares. But they could not make a picture. The pieces did not match.

"This is a weird game," Ben said. "How do you play it?"

"Maybe we can ask Dad. He knows many games," Lily said.

They ran downstairs with the box and the board. They found Dad in the living room, reading a book.

"Dad, Dad, look what we found!" they shouted.

Dad looked at the box and the board. He smiled.

"That's not a puzzle, kids. That's a game called chess. It's a very old and smart game. Do you want to learn how to play it?" he asked.

"Yes, yes, please!" Ben and Lily said.

Dad took the pieces and showed them how to set them up on the board. He explained the names and the moves of each piece. He taught them some rules and some tricks. He let them play against each other and helped them when they got stuck.

Ben and Lily liked the game very much. They thought it was fun and challenging. They played many times and learned new things. They thanked Dad for teaching them.

"Chess is not a weird game. It's a cool game," Ben said.

"I agree. It's a cool game. And you are a cool brother," Lily said.

They hugged each other and smiled. They were happy to play chess and to have each other.
<|end|>


