Tom and Sam are friends. They like to play with toy guns. They have two toy guns: one is red and one is blue. They take turns to shoot each other with the toy guns.

One day, they go to the park to play. They see a big tree with many birds. They want to shoot the birds with their toy guns. They run to the tree and point their toy guns at the birds.

"Bang! Bang!" Tom says, shooting his red toy gun. "I got one!"

"Bang! Bang!" Sam says, shooting his blue toy gun. "I got two!"

The birds are scared. They fly away from the tree. They make loud noises. Tom and Sam laugh. They think they are very good at shooting.

But then, they hear a voice. It is a man. He is angry. He is the owner of the birds. He keeps the birds in a cage near the tree. He lets them out sometimes to fly.

"Hey, you two! Stop shooting my birds!" the man says. "They are not toys! They are alive! They are my pets!"

Tom and Sam are surprised. They did not know the birds belong to the man. They did not know the birds are alive. They thought they are just fun to shoot.

They feel bad. They drop their toy guns. They say sorry to the man.

"We are sorry, mister," Tom says. "We did not know. We just wanted to play."

"We are sorry, mister," Sam says. "We did not mean to hurt your birds."

The man is still angry. But he sees that Tom and Sam are sorry. He sees that they are just kids. He decides to forgive them.

"OK, OK," the man says. "But don't do it again. And don't play with toy guns. They are dangerous. They can hurt people and animals. Play with something else. Play with a ball or a kite or a book."

Tom and Sam nod. They thank the man. They pick up their toy guns. They decide to give them away. They do not want to play with toy guns anymore. They want to play with something else. Something that does not hurt anyone. Something that is fun and safe.
<|end|>


