Tom was a boy who liked to admire things. He admired the birds in the sky, the flowers in the garden, and the toys in his room. But his favorite thing to admire was his grandpa's cane. It was brown and shiny, with a silver handle that looked like a horse. Tom thought it was very cool and wanted to touch it.

One day, Tom was visiting his grandpa's house. His grandpa was in the kitchen, making some tea. Tom saw the cane leaning against the wall in the living room. He ran over to it and grabbed it. He felt the smooth wood and the cold metal. He pretended he was a knight, swinging the cane like a sword.

"Whoosh! Whoosh!" he said, making noises. He felt very brave and happy.

But he did not see the vase on the table. As he swung the cane, he knocked over the vase. It fell to the floor and broke into many pieces. The noise was very loud.

"Oh no!" Tom said. He dropped the cane and looked at the mess. He felt very scared and sorry.

His grandpa heard the noise and came into the living room. He saw the broken vase and the cane on the floor. He saw Tom's face and knew what had happened.

"Tom, what did you do?" he asked, in a stern voice.

Tom started to cry. He did not know what to say. He knew he had done something bad.

"I'm sorry, Grandpa," he sobbed. "I just wanted to admire your cane. I didn't mean to break your vase."

His grandpa looked at him for a moment. Then he sighed and knelt down. He hugged Tom and wiped his tears.

"It's okay, Tom," he said, in a soft voice. "I know you didn't mean it. The vase was old and not very important. But the cane is very special to me. It was a gift from your grandma, before she went to heaven. She loved horses, just like you. That's why it has a horse handle. Do you want to hear a story about her and the cane?"

Tom nodded, sniffling. He felt a little better. He loved his grandpa and his grandma. He wanted to hear their story.

His grandpa smiled and picked up the cane. He took Tom to the couch and sat down. He put Tom on his lap and wrapped his arm around him. He held the cane in his other hand and pointed to the handle.

"See this horse?" he began. "This is how I met your grandma. It was a long time ago, when I was young and strong. I was walking in the park, when I saw a beautiful girl riding a horse. She had long hair and a bright smile. She looked like an angel. I was so amazed by her that I stopped and stared. I did not see the open gate behind me. A dog ran out of the gate and barked at me. It scared me so much that I fell to the ground. The girl saw me and stopped her horse. She got off and came to help me. She asked me if I was okay. I said yes, but I was too shy to say anything else. She laughed and said I was lucky. She said her horse was very gentle and would not hurt me. She said his name was Cane, because he had a white stripe on his nose that looked like a cane. She said he was her best friend. She said she loved him very much. She asked me if I wanted to pet him. I said yes, and I reached out my hand. Cane nuzzled my hand and licked it. He was very warm and soft. The girl smiled and said he liked me. She said I was lucky again. She said her name was Rose, and she asked me mine. I said I was Jack, and I smiled back. She said she liked my name. She said she liked me. She asked me if I wanted to ride with her. I said yes, and I got up. She helped me on the horse and got on behind me. She wrapped her arms around me and held the reins. She whispered in my ear and told me to hold on. She said we were going to have fun. She said she liked me very much. She kissed my cheek and made me blush. She kicked the horse and made him run. We ran through the park, with the wind in our hair and the sun on our faces. We laughed and talked and sang. We felt very happy and free. We felt like we had known each other forever. We felt like we were in love."

Tom listened to his grandpa's story with wide eyes and open mouth. He thought it was the most wonderful story he had ever heard. He admired his grandpa and his grandma. He
<|end|>


