Lily liked math very much. She liked to count and add and take away. She had a bright book with math games and pictures. She wanted to play with her book every day.

But her mom said no. She said Lily had to do other things too. She had to play outside, and read stories, and help with chores. She said math was good, but not all the time. She said Lily could play with her book only after dinner.

Lily was sad. She did not like to wait. She wanted to play with her book now. She tried to sneak her book into her room, but her mom saw her. She said, "Lily, what are you doing? You know the rule. No math until after dinner."

Lily said, "But mom, I love math. It is fun and easy. Please, can I play with my book now? Just for a little bit?"

Her mom shook her head. She said, "No, Lily. You have to learn to do other things too. Math is not the only thing in the world. Now, put your book away and go play outside. Maybe you can find some friends to play with."

Lily did not want to go outside. She did not want to find friends. She wanted to play with her book. She put her book away, but she was not happy. She went outside, but she did not play. She sat on the grass and looked at the sky. She wished she had her book.

Then, she saw something. She saw a bright star in the sky. It was shining and twinkling. It was beautiful. She wondered how many stars there were in the sky. She wondered if she could count them. She wondered if she could do math with them.

She smiled. She had an idea. She ran back to the house and got her book. She hid it under her shirt. She ran back to the grass and lay down. She opened her book and looked at the star. She started to play with her book and the star. She did math with them. She was happy.

She did not see her mom coming. She did not hear her mom saying, "Lily, what are you doing? You know the rule. No math until after dinner."

She did not know what to say. She was caught. She was in trouble. She closed her book and looked at her mom. She said, "But mom, I was not playing with my book. I was playing with the star. The star is bright and pretty. The star is math too."
<|end|>


