Lily wanted to paint a picture of her dog, Max. She took her red brush and dipped it in the paint. She tried to make a circle for Max's head, but it was hard. The brush was too big and the paint was too wet. She struggled to make the circle look like Max.

"Help me, Mommy!" Lily cried. "I can't paint Max!"

Mommy came over and looked at Lily's picture. She smiled and hugged Lily.

"You are doing great, sweetie. Painting is fun, but it can also be tricky. Do you want me to show you how to use a smaller brush?"

"Yes, please!" Lily said. She put down her red brush and picked up a blue one. Mommy took another blue brush and held Lily's hand.

"Let's make some dots for Max's eyes and nose. And then we can make some lines for his ears and tail. Like this, see?" Mommy said, guiding Lily's brush on the paper.

Lily followed Mommy's movements and watched as Max's face and body appeared on the paper. She giggled and clapped her hands.

"Look, Mommy! I painted Max! He is so cute!"

Mommy kissed Lily's cheek and praised her.

"You did a wonderful job, Lily. I love your picture of Max. He is very cute. And you are very smart and creative. Do you want to paint more?"

Lily nodded and smiled. She loved painting with Mommy. She picked up her red brush again and decided to paint a flower for Max. She was happy and proud of her art.
