Sara and Ben were friends. They liked to play together at the park. One day, they saw a big sign that said "Lollipop Contest". The sign had a picture of a lollipop with many colors.

"Wow, look at that!" Sara said. "I want to win a lollipop!"

"Me too!" Ben said. "Let's go and try!"

They ran to the table where a lady was giving out papers. The papers had questions about animals and colors. Sara and Ben knew a lot about animals and colors. They took the papers and a pencil and started to write the answers.

A boy named Max was also there. He wanted to win a lollipop too. But he was rude. He did not say hello to Sara and Ben. He did not wait for his turn. He grabbed a paper and a pencil and pushed Sara and Ben aside.

"Move, you are too slow!" he said. "I will win the lollipop, not you!"

Sara and Ben felt sad and angry. They did not like Max. They moved to another spot and finished their papers. They gave them to the lady and waited for the results.

The lady looked at the papers and smiled. She said, "Thank you for participating in the lollipop contest. You all did very well. But there is only one winner. And the winner is..."

She paused and looked at the papers again. She said, "The winner is... Sara and Ben!"

Sara and Ben were surprised and happy. They jumped and hugged each other. They had succeeded!

The lady gave them each a big lollipop with many colors. They thanked her and licked their lollipops.

Max was shocked and angry. He had not succeeded. He had written the wrong answers. He had been rude. He did not get a lollipop.

He stomped his feet and cried. He said, "That's not fair! I want a lollipop too!"

But the lady said, "Sorry, Max. You did not win. You did not follow the rules. You were rude to Sara and Ben. You need to learn to be nice and respectful. Maybe next time you will do better."

Sara and Ben felt sorry for Max. They decided to share their lollipops with him. They said, "Here, Max. You can have some of our lollipops. But you have to say sorry and be nice to us."

Max looked at them and felt ashamed. He said, "Sorry, Sara and Ben. I was rude to you. I will be nice to you from now on."

He took a bite of their lollipops and smiled. He said, "Thank you, Sara and Ben. You are good friends."

They all smiled and became friends. They played together at the park and enjoyed their lollipops. They learned to be kind and respectful to each other. They had a good day.
<|end|>


