Anna and Ben were playing with magnets on the floor. They liked to see how the magnets stuck together or pushed away. Anna had a big red magnet and Ben had a small blue one.

"Look, Anna, my magnet can reach your magnet from here!" Ben said, holding his magnet close to hers.

Anna moved her magnet away. "No, Ben, I don't want to play with your magnet. It is too small and weak. My magnet is bigger and stronger. It can reach anything!"

Ben felt sad. He wanted to play with Anna, but she was not nice to him. He looked around and saw a metal spoon on the table. He had an idea.

"Anna, look what I can do!" Ben said, standing up and reaching for the spoon with his magnet.

But the spoon was too far and too high for Ben. He stretched his arm and leaned forward, but he could not reach it. He lost his balance and fell to the floor, dropping his magnet.

"Ow!" Ben cried, rubbing his head.

Anna heard Ben's cry and turned around. She saw him on the floor, looking troubled. She felt sorry for him. She picked up her magnet and went to him.

"Are you okay, Ben?" Anna asked, giving him her magnet.

Ben smiled and took her magnet. "Thank you, Anna. Your magnet is very nice. Do you want to play with my magnet?"

Anna nodded. "Yes, Ben. I'm sorry I was mean to you. Your magnet is very cool. Can we share our magnets?"

Ben hugged Anna. "Yes, we can. You are my best friend."

They played with their magnets happily, making them stick together and push away. They learned that magnets can reach many things, but friendship can reach even more.
<|end|>


