Tom and Lily were playing in the park. They liked to slide, swing and run. But it was a cold day and they did not have warm clothes. They started to tremble and shiver.

"Let's go home, Tom. I'm cold and hungry," Lily said.

"Me too, Lily. But we have to walk a long way. And we have no money for the bus," Tom said.

They saw a shiny thing on the ground. It was a penny. Tom picked it up and showed it to Lily.

"Look, Lily. A penny. Maybe we can buy something with it," Tom said.

They went to the shop near the park. They saw many things they liked. Candy, cookies, juice, toys. But they were all too expensive. The cheapest thing was a small loaf of bread. It cost two pennies.

"Can we have this, please?" Tom asked the shopkeeper.

The shopkeeper looked at them. He saw their dirty clothes, their red noses, their trembling hands. He felt sorry for them.

"Sure, kids. Here you go. And take this too," he said. He gave them the bread and a warm scarf.

"Thank you, sir. Thank you very much," Tom and Lily said.

They wrapped the scarf around their necks and ate the bread. They felt warmer and happier. They smiled at each other and hugged.

"Let's go home, Lily. We have a penny and a scarf. We are lucky," Tom said.

"Yes, Tom. We are lucky. And we have each other," Lily said.
<|end|>


