Tommy loves to watch cartoons on TV. He likes the funny animals and the bright colors. He always laughs when they do silly things. Sometimes he pretends to be a cartoon animal too.

One day, Tommy found a big bag of candy in the kitchen. He was very happy. He wanted to eat all the candy and watch cartoons. He took the bag to the living room and turned on the TV. He saw his favorite cartoon. It was about a dog and a cat who were friends.

Tommy opened the bag and took out a candy. It was red and shiny. He put it in his mouth and started to chew. It was very sweet and sticky. He liked it a lot. He took out another candy and chewed it too. He did not notice that the candy was making his teeth dirty.

Soon, Tommy had eaten many candies. He felt sick. His tummy hurt. He did not want to watch cartoons anymore. He wanted to lie down. He turned off the TV and went to his bed. He closed his eyes and tried to sleep.

His mom came home and saw the empty bag of candy on the floor. She was angry. She went to Tommy's room and saw him in his bed. He looked pale and sad. She saw his teeth and they were black and brown. She was worried.

"Tommy, what did you do?" she asked.

"I ate candy and watched cartoons," Tommy said in a weak voice.

"That was not a good idea, Tommy. Candy is bad for your teeth and your tummy. You should not eat so much. You should eat healthy food and drink water. And you should not watch too much TV. You should play and read and learn. That is more interesting and fun," she said.

"I'm sorry, mom. I did not know. I thought candy and cartoons were good. But they made me feel bad. I don't want them anymore. I want to be healthy and happy," Tommy said.

"I'm glad you understand, Tommy. I love you and I want you to be well. Come on, let's go to the bathroom and brush your teeth. Then I will make you some soup and read you a story. How does that sound?" she said.

"That sounds good, mom. I love you too. Thank you for taking care of me," Tommy said.

They hugged and went to the bathroom. Tommy brushed his teeth and felt better. He ate some soup and listened to a story. He learned something new and he smiled. He decided to eat less candy and watch less cartoons. He decided to do more interesting and fun things. He was a good boy.
<|end|>


