<|asst|>
Ben loves his truck. He plays with it every day. He makes it go fast and loud. He does not like to share his truck with anyone.

One day, Ben goes to the park with his mom. He sees some kids playing with other toys. He wants to join them, but he does not want to invite them to play with his truck. He thinks they will break it or take it away.

He goes to a corner and plays with his truck alone. He makes it go fast and loud. He does not look at the other kids. He does not smile.

The other kids see Ben and his truck. They think it looks fun. They want to play with him, but they are afraid to ask. They think he is mean and bitter. They stay away from him.

Ben gets bored and lonely. He wonders why no one wants to play with him. He looks at the other kids and sees them laughing and sharing. He feels sad and sorry.

He decides to be brave and kind. He goes to the other kids and invites them to play with his truck. He says he is sorry for being mean and bitter. He says he wants to be friends.

The other kids are happy and surprised. They accept his invite and thank him. They play with his truck and their toys. They take turns and help each other. They have fun.

Ben learns a lesson. He learns that sharing is caring. He learns that inviting is nice. He learns that playing with friends is better than playing alone. He smiles.
<|end|>


