<|asst|>
Jill and Ben were twins who liked to play dress-up. One day, they found a big box of old clothes in the attic. They tried on hats, coats, scarves and shoes. Jill saw a white veil and put it on her head. She felt like a princess.

"Look at me, Ben!" she said. "I am a princess and you are my prince!"

Ben looked at her and smiled. He liked to make his sister happy. But he could not hear her very well. Ben was deaf. He used his hands to talk.

"You are pretty, Jill," he said with his hands. "But the veil is too long. You might trip and fall."

Jill did not listen to him. She was too busy pretending to be a princess. She ran around the attic with the veil trailing behind her. She did not see the old lamp on the floor. She tripped over it and fell. The veil ripped and the lamp broke. Jill hurt her knee and started to cry.

Ben ran to her and hugged her. He felt sorry for her. He used his hands to say, "Are you OK, Jill? I told you to be careful."

Jill looked at him and nodded. She felt ashamed. She had not listened to her brother. He was right. The veil was too long. She had been silly and rude.

"I am sorry, Ben," she said. "You are a good brother. You tried to help me. I should have listened to you. I love you."

Ben smiled and kissed her cheek. He felt happy. He loved his sister too. He used his hands to say, "I love you too, Jill. It is OK. We can fix the veil and the lamp. We can still play dress-up. But next time, let us be careful."

Jill and Ben learned a lesson that day. They learned to listen to each other and to be respectful. They learned that being a princess or a prince is not about wearing a veil or a crown. It is about being kind and loving.
<|end|>


