Tom and Mia are playing in the garden. They see a big stick on the ground. Tom says, "Let's balance on the stick. It will be fun." Mia says, "OK, but be careful. The stick is long and thin."

Tom and Mia take turns to balance on the stick. They try to walk from one end to the other without falling. Tom is good at balancing. He can walk fast and steady. Mia is not so good. She walks slowly and wobbles. She feels dizzy.

Mia says, "Tom, I don't like this game. I feel dizzy. Can we play something else?" Tom says, "No, this game is fun. You just need to practice more. Come on, try again."

Mia tries again, but she is too dizzy. She loses her balance and falls off the stick. She bumps her head on the ground. She cries. Tom says, "Oh no, Mia, are you OK? I'm sorry, I didn't mean to make you fall."

Tom runs to get his mom. His mom comes with a thermometer. She checks Mia's temperature. She says, "Mia, you have a fever. That's why you feel dizzy. You need to rest and drink some water. Come on, let's go inside."

Tom says, "I'm sorry, Mia. I hope you feel better soon. Can I play with you later?" Mia says, "It's OK, Tom. I'm not mad at you. You can play with me later. But no more balancing on the stick, OK?" Tom says, "OK, Mia. No more balancing on the stick. I love you." Mia says, "I love you too, Tom."
<|end|>


