Tom and Sue were twins who liked to play in the park. They saw a big slide that looked very fun. They ran to the slide and waited for their turn.

"Can I go first?" Tom asked Sue.

"Okay, but be careful," Sue said.

Tom climbed up the ladder to the top of the slide. He saw a shiny handle on the side of the slide. He wondered what it was for. He grabbed the handle and pulled it.

Suddenly, the slide moved and made a loud noise. Tom was scared and let go of the handle. He slid down very fast and hit the ground hard. He cried and felt pain in his arm.

Sue saw what happened and ran to Tom. She hugged him and tried to make him feel better.

"Are you okay, Tom?" Sue asked.

"No, it hurts a lot," Tom said.

A jolly man in a uniform came to help them. He was a park ranger. He saw the handle and the slide.

"Who pulled this handle?" he asked.

"I did," Tom said.

The park ranger was not jolly anymore. He was angry.

"This handle is not for playing. It is for emergencies. It makes the slide fold up and lock. You could have been hurt very badly. You were very naughty and foolish," he said.

He took Tom and Sue to their mom and dad. He told them what Tom did. Mom and dad were not happy. They scolded Tom and took him to the doctor. The doctor said Tom had a broken arm. He put a cast on his arm and told him to rest.

Tom was very sorry and sad. He learned a lesson. He learned not to touch things he did not know. He learned to listen to his sister. He learned to be careful and safe. He hoped he would never pull a handle like that again.
<|end|>


