Tom and Sam were brothers. They liked to play outside, but today it was raining. They were bored. They looked around the house for something fun to do.

"Let's play with the scissors!" Tom said. He found a pair of scissors in the kitchen. They were shiny and sharp.

"No, Tom, that's bad!" Sam said. "Mom said scissors are not toys. They can hurt you. Put them back!"

But Tom did not listen. He ran away with the scissors. He wanted to cut something. He saw a big red sock on the fireplace. It was Dad's sock. He put it there for Santa.

"Ha ha, I will cut the sock!" Tom said. He climbed on a chair and reached for the sock. He did not see the chimney behind him.

Sam followed him and saw what he was doing. He was scared. He tried to stop him.

"Tom, stop, stop!" Sam said. "You will fall in the chimney! It is dark and dirty and cold! You will get stuck!"

But Tom did not hear him. He cut the sock with the scissors. He was happy. He laughed. But then he lost his balance. He fell backwards. He fell in the chimney.

"Help, help!" Tom cried. He was not happy. He was sad. He was scared. He was sorry.

Sam ran to get Mom. Mom came and saw what happened. She was angry and worried. She called Dad. Dad came and saw what happened. He was angry and worried too. He got a ladder and a rope. He climbed on the roof and looked in the chimney. He saw Tom. He was dirty and cold and crying.

"Dad, Dad, I'm sorry, I'm sorry!" Tom said.

Dad tied the rope around Tom and pulled him out. He hugged him and kissed him. He was glad he was safe.

"Tom, you were very naughty and very silly!" Dad said. "You could have hurt yourself or the house! You must never play with scissors or cut things that are not yours! And you must never go near the chimney! Do you understand?"

"Yes, Dad, I understand," Tom said. "I'm sorry, Dad. I'm sorry, Mom. I'm sorry, Sam. I'm sorry, Santa."

Mom and Dad and Sam forgave him. They cleaned him and warmed him. They gave him a new sock and a hug. They told him they loved him.

Tom learned his lesson. He never played with scissors or cut things that were not his again. He never went near the chimney again. He was a good boy. He was not bored. He was happy.
<|end|>


