Sara and Tom are playing with their toys in the living room. Sara has a big doll with long hair and a pink dress. Tom has a small car with four wheels and a horn. Sara likes her doll very much and does not want anyone to touch it. Tom likes his car very much and does not want anyone to touch it.

"Can I see your doll?" Tom asks Sara. He wants to touch the doll's hair and dress.

"No, you can't!" Sara says. "This is my doll and she is very clean. You have dirty hands and you will make her dirty too."

"Can I see your car?" Sara asks Tom. She wants to touch the car's wheels and horn.

"No, you can't!" Tom says. "This is my car and he is very fast. You have slow hands and you will make him slow too."

Sara and Tom are not happy. They do not want to share their toys. They turn away from each other and play alone.

But then they hear a loud noise from the kitchen. It is their mom. She is making cookies for them. They smell the cookies and they feel hungry.

"Come here, Sara and Tom!" their mom calls. "I have a surprise for you!"

Sara and Tom run to the kitchen. They see a big plate of cookies on the table. They look yummy and sweet.

"Wow, cookies!" Sara and Tom say. "Can we have some, mom?"

"Yes, you can, but first you have to do something for me," their mom says. "You have to wash your hands and be nice to each other. Can you do that?"

Sara and Tom look at each other. They remember their toys and their words. They feel sorry and ashamed.

"Yes, mom, we can do that," they say. "We are sorry for being mean. We will share our toys and be friends."

They hug each other and say sorry. Then they wash their hands and sit at the table. Their mom gives them each a cookie and a glass of milk. They smile and thank their mom. They eat their cookies and drink their milk. They are happy and full.

They learn a lesson. They learn that sharing is caring and that cookies are better than toys.
