Tom likes to play the piano. He has a small piano in his room. He can play some songs with his fingers. He wants to learn more songs.

One day, he sees a big piano in his aunt's house. He asks his aunt, "Can I play your piano?"

His aunt says, "Yes, you can, but be careful. This piano is very difficult. You have to use both hands and feet. You have to read the notes on the paper. You have to listen to the sound."

Tom says, "I want to try. I can do it."

He sits on the piano bench. He puts his hands on the keys. He tries to play a song. But he does not know what to do. He presses the wrong keys. He makes a loud noise. He does not use his feet. He does not look at the paper. He does not hear the sound.

His aunt says, "Tom, stop. You are making a mess. You are not playing the piano. You are just hitting the keys. You have to learn the rules. You have to practice a lot. You have to be patient."

Tom says, "But I want to play the piano. I want to play like you. I want to play beautiful songs."

His aunt says, "I understand. But you have to start with the small piano. You have to learn the easy songs. You have to get better step by step. Then, when you are ready, you can play the big piano. You can play the difficult songs. You can play like me. But you have to work hard. Do you want to do that?"

Tom thinks for a moment. He says, "Yes, I do. I want to work hard. I want to get better. I want to play the piano."

His aunt says, "Good. Then let's go back to your room. I will teach you some songs. I will help you practice. I will be proud of you."

Tom smiles. He says, "Thank you, aunt. You are very kind. You are a good teacher. I love you."

He hugs his aunt. He takes her hand. He goes back to his room. He plays the small piano. He learns some songs. He practices a lot. He gets better. He is happy.
<|end|>


