Tom and Mia are playing in the garden. They have a big box and some sticks. They pretend the box is a rocket and the sticks are fire.

"Ready to blast off?" Tom asks Mia.

"Yes, yes, yes!" Mia says. She puts on a helmet made of a pot. Tom puts on a hat made of a bowl.

They sit in the box and count. "Three, two, one, go!" They shout. They make loud noises with their mouths. "Zoom, zoom, zoom!"

They imagine they are flying to the moon. They see stars and planets. They feel the wind and the heat.

But then, something goes wrong. The sticks catch fire. The box starts to burn. Smoke and ash come out.

"Help, help, help!" Tom and Mia scream. They jump out of the box. They run to the house.

Mum and Dad hear them. They come out and see the fire. They are angry and scared.

"What have you done?" Mum asks. "You could have hurt yourselves. You have to be careful with fire. It is dangerous."

"We are sorry, Mum. We are sorry, Dad." Tom and Mia say. They hug Mum and Dad. They are sad and sorry.

Mum and Dad put out the fire. They throw away the box and the sticks. They take Tom and Mia inside. They wash their faces and hands. They give them some water and cookies.

They talk to them about fire safety. They tell them to never play with fire. They tell them to always ask for permission. They tell them to use their imagination in a safe way.

Tom and Mia listen and nod. They understand. They say they will be more careful next time. They say they love Mum and Dad.

Mum and Dad smile and hug them. They say they love them too. They say they are proud of their imagination. They say they can still play rocket, but with something else.

They give them some paper and crayons. They help them make a new rocket. They draw stars and planets. They stick them on the wall.

They sit in the paper rocket and count. "Three, two, one, go!" They shout. They make loud noises with their mouths. "Zoom, zoom, zoom!"

They imagine they are flying to the moon. They see stars and planets. They feel the wind and the heat.

But this time, there is no fire. There is no smoke. There is no ash.

There is only fun.
<|end|>


