Anna likes to play the piano. The piano is big and black and makes nice sounds. Anna's grandma has an old piano in her house. Grandma says the piano is older than her.

One day, Anna goes to visit Grandma with her mom. Grandma is happy to see them. She gives them hugs and cookies. She says, "Do you want to play the piano, Anna?"

Anna nods and runs to the piano. She sits on the stool and puts her fingers on the keys. She plays some songs that she knows. She plays Twinkle Twinkle Little Star and Mary Had a Little Lamb. She sings along with the piano.

Grandma and Mom listen and smile. They clap for Anna when she finishes. They say, "You are very good, Anna. You play the piano so well."

Anna feels proud and happy. She says, "Thank you, Grandma. Thank you, Mom. I love the piano. Can I play some more?"

Grandma says, "Of course, my dear. You can play as much as you want. The piano likes you too. It likes to make music with you."

Anna hugs Grandma and says, "I love you, Grandma. And I love your old piano. It is very special."

Grandma hugs Anna back and says, "I love you too, Anna. And I'm glad you love my old piano. It is very special to me too. It was my mom's piano. She taught me how to play when I was a little girl. And now I can teach you."
<|end|>


