Lily and Ben are playing in the park. They like to run and jump and slide. Lily sees a big hill and wants to roll down. She says to Ben, "Come on, let's roll down the hill!"

Ben is scared. He thinks the hill is too high and steep. He says to Lily, "No, I don't want to. It looks scary. You go first."

Lily is brave. She says to Ben, "OK, I will go first. You watch me. It will be fun." She runs to the top of the hill and lies down on her back. She puts her arms to her sides and closes her eyes. She starts to roll down the hill.

But the hill is not smooth. It has rocks and sticks and bumps. Lily feels them hit her back and legs and head. She says, "Ow, ow, ow!" She tries to stop, but she can't. She rolls faster and faster.

Ben sees Lily rolling down the hill. He hears her say, "Ow, ow, ow!" He is worried. He runs to the bottom of the hill to catch her. He says, "Lily, Lily, are you OK?"

Lily stops rolling. She opens her eyes and sees Ben. She is dizzy and sore. She says, "Ben, I'm not OK. I hurt all over. That was not fun. That was bad."

Ben hugs Lily. He says, "I'm sorry, Lily. You are brave, but that was not a good idea. Let me help you. Do you want to go home?"

Lily nods. She says, "Yes, please. I want to go home. I want to see Mommy. I want to lie on the couch and suck my thumb. That will make me feel better."

Ben says, "OK, let's go home. I will hold your hand. I will tell Mommy what happened. She will make you feel better too. She will give you a kiss and a band-aid and a hug."

Lily and Ben walk home. They are sad and hurt, but they are also glad. They are glad they have each other. They are glad they have Mommy. They are glad they learned a lesson. They will not roll down the hill again.
<|end|>


