Tom and Sue are friends. They like to play outside in the sun. But today it is very hot. They feel thirsty and tired.

"Let's have some juice," Tom says. "I have some in my bag."

"Good idea," Sue says. "But where can we drink it? There is no shade here."

They look around. They see a big tree. It has green leaves and red apples. It makes a lot of shade.

"Let's go there," Tom says. "Maybe we can have some apples too. They look yummy."

They run to the tree. They sit under the leaves. They drink their juice. They feel better.

"Can we have some apples?" Sue asks. "They are so red and shiny."

"I don't know," Tom says. "Maybe they belong to someone. Maybe they are not ripe. Maybe they are sour."

But Sue does not listen. She reaches for an apple. She pulls it hard. She bites it.

"Ow!" she cries. "This apple is not yummy. It is yucky. It hurts my teeth."

Tom looks at the apple. He sees a worm. It is brown and slimy. It wiggles in the apple.

"Yuck!" he says. "That is not an apple. That is a worm house. You have a worm in your mouth."

Sue spits out the apple. She spits out the worm. She feels sick.

"Let's go home," she says. "I don't want any more juice or apples. I want some water and a hug."

They leave the tree. They walk home. They learn a lesson. They do not have any more worms.
<|end|>


