<|asst|>
Anna liked to count. She counted her fingers, her toes, her toys, and her books. She counted everything she saw. One day, she wanted to count the bubbles in the sink. She asked her mom if she could play with the soap and water.

"Okay, but be careful," her mom said. "Don't make a mess or spill the water. And don't use too much soap. It makes thick bubbles that are hard to wash away."

Anna nodded and ran to the sink. She turned on the faucet and poured some soap. She watched the bubbles grow and pop. She counted them out loud. "One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten!"

She was having so much fun that she didn't notice the water rising in the sink. She kept pouring more soap and making more bubbles. She counted higher and higher. "Eleven, twelve, thirteen, fourteen, fifteen, sixteen, seventeen, eighteen, nineteen, twenty!"

Suddenly, she heard a loud splash. She looked down and saw the water overflowing from the sink. It spilled on the floor and made a big puddle. She gasped and dropped the soap. She ran to her mom and cried. "Mommy, mommy, I'm sorry! I made a mess!"

Her mom came to the kitchen and saw the water and the bubbles. She sighed and shook her head. She grabbed a towel and started to clean up. She said to Anna, "I told you not to use too much soap. It makes thick bubbles that are hard to wash away. Now we have to dry the floor and the sink. And you have to stop counting for a while. You need to learn to pay attention to what you're doing."

Anna felt bad and said, "I'm sorry, mommy. I won't do it again. I just wanted to count the bubbles. They were so pretty and fun."

Her mom smiled and hugged her. She said, "I know, sweetie. Counting is good, but not when it causes trouble. Next time, why don't you count something else? Like the stars in the sky, or the flowers in the garden, or the birds in the tree. There are many things to count that won't make a mess."

Anna nodded and said, "Okay, mommy. I'll count something else. Can I count the towels you're using?"

Her mom laughed and said, "Sure, you can count the towels. But only up to ten. That's enough for today."
<|end|>


