Lily and Ben were playing with their toys in the living room. They liked to make up stories with their dolls and cars and animals. Lily had a big box of cloth that she used to dress up her dolls and make tents and blankets. Ben had a small bag of buttons that he used to add details to his cars and animals.

One day, they found a mysterious cloth in the box. It was shiny and soft and had strange patterns on it. Lily wanted to use it for her doll's dress, but Ben wanted to use it for his car's seat. They both grabbed the cloth and pulled it hard.

"Let go, Lily! This is my cloth!" Ben shouted.

"No, Ben! This is my cloth! I saw it first!" Lily yelled.

They pulled and pulled until the cloth ripped in half. They both fell back and looked at the torn cloth. They felt sad and angry.

"Look what you did, Ben! You ruined the cloth!" Lily cried.

"Look what you did, Lily! You ruined the cloth!" Ben sobbed.

They both threw their half of the cloth on the floor and turned away from each other. They didn't want to play anymore.

Mom came into the living room and saw the mess. She saw the torn cloth and the toys and the tears. She picked up the cloth and looked at it.

"Where did you find this cloth, kids?" Mom asked.

"In the box, Mom," Lily and Ben said.

Mom smiled and said, "This is a special cloth, kids. It's from Grandma. She gave it to me when I was little. She said it was from a faraway land where she used to live. She said it had magic in it. She said it could make you happy if you shared it with someone you love."

Lily and Ben looked at each other. They felt sorry for what they did. They remembered how much they loved Grandma and how much they loved each other.

"Can we fix the cloth, Mom?" Lily asked.

"Can we share the cloth, Mom?" Ben asked.

Mom nodded and said, "Of course, kids. We can sew the cloth together and make something new. We can make a pillow or a scarf or a banner. We can make something that you can both use and enjoy. We can make something that will remind you of Grandma and her love."

Lily and Ben hugged Mom and said, "Thank you, Mom. We love you. We love Grandma. We love the cloth."

They took the cloth and their toys and went to Mom's sewing room. They helped Mom stitch the cloth and add some buttons and ribbons. They made a beautiful banner that said, "We are family." They hung the banner on the wall and smiled. They felt the magic of the cloth and the love of Grandma. They played happily together and made up new stories with their dolls and cars and animals.
<|end|>


