<|asst|>
Ben and Lily were playing with their toy animals. They had a big lion, a small mouse, a long snake and a shiny fish. They made noises and pretended the animals were talking to each other.

"Roar! I am the king of the jungle. I can eat anyone I want," said the lion.

"Squeak! You are very big and scary. But you are also very nice. You do not eat me or my friends," said the mouse.

"Hisss! I am the queen of the forest. I can bite anyone I want," said the snake.

"Blub! You are very long and slimy. But you are also very smart. You do not bite me or my friends," said the fish.

They were having fun until Ben saw a new toy on the shelf. It was a scale. It had two plates and a needle. Ben wanted to play with it.

"Look, Lily, a scale! We can weigh the animals and see who is the heaviest," said Ben.

He grabbed the scale and put the lion on one plate and the mouse on the other. The needle moved to the lion's side.

"Ha! The lion is much heavier than the mouse. He is the strongest," said Ben.

He took the mouse and put the snake on the other plate. The needle moved to the snake's side.

"Wow! The snake is heavier than the mouse too. She is the longest," said Ben.

He took the snake and put the fish on the other plate. The needle did not move.

"Huh? The fish is not heavier than the mouse. He is the lightest," said Ben.

He picked up the fish and looked at it. He saw that it had a button on its belly. He pressed it and the fish opened its mouth. Inside, there was a sharp hook.

"Ouch! The fish bit me. He is dangerous," said Ben.

He dropped the fish and cried. Lily ran to him and hugged him.

"I'm sorry, Ben. The fish is not a toy. It is a trap. It is for catching real fish. Daddy told me not to touch it. You should not touch it either," said Lily.

She took the fish and put it back on the shelf. She took a band-aid and put it on Ben's finger.

"Does it hurt?" she asked.

"A little. But it is okay. Thank you, Lily," said Ben.

He smiled and hugged her back.

"I forgive you, Lily. You are a good sister. Can we play with the animals again?" he asked.

"Of course, Ben. You are a good brother. Let's play with the animals again," she said.

They took the animals and played with them. They made noises and pretended the animals were talking to each other.

"Roar! I am the king of the jungle. But I am also very kind. I share my food with the mouse and the snake," said the lion.

"Squeak! I am the smallest of the animals. But I am also very brave. I help the lion and the snake when they are in trouble," said the mouse.

"Hisss! I am the queen of the forest. But I am also very wise. I teach the lion and the mouse how to hide and how to find water," said the snake.

"Blub! I am the lightest of the animals. But I am also very shiny. I make the lion and the mouse and the snake happy with my colors and my bubbles," said the fish.

They were happy and they played until it was time for dinner. They put the animals away and went to the kitchen. They told their mommy and daddy about their adventure with the scale and the fish. They said they were sorry for touching the fish and they learned their lesson. Their mommy and daddy hugged them and said they were proud of them. They said they forgave them and they loved them. They ate their dinner and they had a good night.
<|end|>


