Tom is a lonely boy. He has no friends to play with. He likes to play with his toys, but they are not fun like real friends. He wishes he had someone to talk to and share his toys with.

One day, he finds a new toy in his room. It is a green dragon with big wings and a long tail. Tom is very happy. He thinks the dragon is his new friend. He gives the dragon a name: Snap. He says, "Hello, Snap. Do you want to play with me?"

Snap does not answer. He does not move. He does not make any sound. Tom is sad. He thinks Snap is broken. He tries to make Snap talk. He shakes him, he tickles him, he pulls his tail. But Snap still does not talk.

Tom gets angry. He thinks Snap is a bad toy. He does not want to play with him anymore. He throws him on the floor. He says, "You are a mean dragon. You are not my friend. Go away!"

Snap does not like being thrown. He does not like being called mean. He does not like being lonely. He decides to show Tom that he is not a bad toy. He decides to talk.

He opens his mouth and says, "Roar!" He flaps his wings and says, "Fly!" He swings his tail and says, "Smash!"

Tom is scared. He did not know Snap could talk. He did not know Snap could fly. He did not know Snap could smash. He runs to his bed and hides under the covers. He says, "Help! Help! The dragon is alive!"

Snap feels sorry for Tom. He did not mean to scare him. He just wanted to play with him. He flies to his bed and says, "Don't be afraid. I am not a mean dragon. I am your friend. Please play with me."

Tom peeks from under the covers. He sees Snap's big eyes and soft nose. He hears Snap's gentle voice and kind words. He thinks maybe Snap is not so bad after all. He thinks maybe Snap is lonely too. He says, "OK, Snap. I will play with you. But you have to be nice. And you have to be patient. I am still learning how to play with a dragon."

Snap nods and smiles. He says, "OK, Tom. I will be nice. And I will be patient. I am still learning how to play with a boy."

Tom and Snap become friends. They play with each other and share their toys. They talk and laugh and have fun. They are not lonely anymore. They are happy.
<|end|>


