Tom and Mia like to play with cars. They have many cars of different colors and sizes. They make roads with blocks and books and zoom their cars on them. They pretend to be drivers and talk to each other.

"Look at my car, Mia!" Tom says. "It is purple and big and fast. It can zoom past all the other cars. Vroom, vroom!"

"Wow, Tom, your car is nice!" Mia says. "But my car is better. It is red and small and smart. It can zoom under the bridges and around the corners. Beep, beep!"

They zoom their cars together and have fun. But then they hear a loud noise. It is a scary noise. It sounds like a roar. They look up and see a big, black dog. The dog is angry and barks at them. It runs towards them and their cars.

"Help, Mia, help!" Tom cries. "The dog is scary! It wants to bite us and our cars!"

"Run, Tom, run!" Mia shouts. "Grab your car and follow me! We have to hide!"

They pick up their cars and run away from the dog. They find a safe place behind the sofa. They hug each other and their cars. They are scared and sad.

"Tom, Mia, what's wrong?" Mom asks. She hears them crying and comes to see. She sees the dog and shooes it away. She picks up Tom and Mia and hugs them. She is kind and gentle.

"Mom, the dog was scary!" Tom says. "It chased us and our cars!"

"Mom, the dog was mean!" Mia says. "It barked at us and our cars!"

"I'm sorry, Tom and Mia," Mom says. "The dog is not ours. It belongs to the new neighbors. They must have left the gate open. I will talk to them and tell them to keep the dog inside. You are safe now. Don't worry."

She kisses them and their cars. She gives them cookies and milk. She plays with them and their cars. They zoom their cars again and smile. They are happy and brave.
