Sara and Tom are friends. They like to play in the park. One day, they see a man with a cart. He has many pastries on the cart. They smell good.

"Hello, children. Do you want to buy a pastry?" the man says. "They are very tasty and mild. Only one coin each."

Sara and Tom are hungry. They have one coin each. They give the coins to the man. He gives them each a pastry. They say thank you and walk away.

They bite the pastries. They are not tasty and mild. They are sour and hard. They make their mouths hurt. They spit them out.

"Yuck! These pastries are bad!" Sara says.

"Let's go back and tell the man. Maybe he will give us our coins back." Tom says.

They run back to the cart. But the man is gone. He has taken his cart and his pastries. He has sold them all to other children. He has tricked them.

Sara and Tom are sad and angry. They have no pastries and no coins. They have learned a hard lesson. They should not trust strangers who sell things. They go home and tell their parents. Their parents hug them and give them some milk and cookies. But they still feel bad. They wish they had not bought the pastries. The end.
