Tim and Mia liked to play in the forest. They saw many animals and plants. One day, they found a big mushroom. It was red and white and round.

"Wow, look at this mushroom!" Tim said. "It is so big and pretty. I want to ride on it."

"No, I want to ride on it!" Mia said. "It is my mushroom. I saw it first."

They both ran to the mushroom and tried to climb on it. They pushed and pulled and shouted. They were very selfish. They did not want to share.

The mushroom did not like that. It felt their feet and hands and voices. It was angry and sad. It wanted to be left alone.

Suddenly, the mushroom shook and bounced. Tim and Mia fell off the mushroom. They landed on the ground. They were scared and hurt.

They looked at the mushroom. It had a face. It had eyes and a mouth and a nose. It glared at them.

"Go away!" the mushroom said. "You are bad children. You are not nice to me or to each other. You do not deserve to ride on me."

Tim and Mia felt sorry. They realized they were wrong. They got up and dusted themselves off.

"We are sorry, mushroom," Tim said. "We were selfish. We should have asked you first. And we should have taken turns."

"Yes, we are sorry, mushroom," Mia said. "We did not mean to hurt you. You are a living thing. You have feelings. We should have respected you."

The mushroom softened. It saw that they were sincere. It smiled a little.

"Thank you for saying sorry," the mushroom said. "That is very kind of you. Maybe you can ride on me another day. But only if you are gentle and careful and fair."

Tim and Mia nodded. They thanked the mushroom and said goodbye. They walked away, holding hands. They learned a lesson. They decided to be more friendly and generous. They hoped to see the mushroom again.
<|end|>


