One day, Ben and Mia went to the park with their mom. They saw a big tent with many flags and balloons. Mom said it was a circus. Ben and Mia wanted to see the circus.

"Can we go, mom? Please, please, please?" they asked.

Mom smiled and said, "Yes, we can go. But first, we have to buy tickets. Wait here for a minute, okay?"

Ben and Mia nodded and waited near a pole. The pole was very high and had a rope on it. Ben wondered what the rope was for. He wanted to touch it.

"Look, Mia, a rope!" he said. "I want to pull it. Maybe something fun will happen."

Mia shook her head. "No, Ben, don't do that. Mom said to wait. The rope might be for the circus. You might break something."

But Ben did not listen. He reached for the rope and pulled it hard. Suddenly, he heard a loud noise. He looked up and saw a big ball falling from the sky. The ball was red and shiny. It was a firework. It was going to strike the tent.

"Ben, what did you do?" Mia cried. "You made a firework go off. It will burn the tent. We have to run."

Ben was scared. He let go of the rope and ran with Mia. They found their mom and told her what happened. Mom was angry and sad.

"Ben, you did a very bad thing. You did not listen to me. You did not listen to Mia. You played with something you did not know. You put yourself and others in danger. You ruined the circus for everyone. How do you feel?"

Ben felt ashamed. He looked at the tent and saw a hole in it. He saw the people running and screaming. He saw the firemen coming to put out the fire. He saw the circus people crying and shouting.

"I feel sorry, mom. I feel sorry, Mia. I feel sorry, circus people. I did not mean to do it. I was curious. I wanted to have fun. But I was wrong. I was foolish. I learned my lesson. I will never do it again."

Mom hugged Ben and Mia. She said, "I'm glad you are safe. I'm glad you are sorry. But sorry is not enough. You have to make up for what you did. You have to apologize to the circus people. You have to help them fix the tent. You have to show them you care. That is the right thing to do."

Ben and Mia nodded. They walked to the circus people and said they were sorry. They offered to help them fix the tent. They offered to share their toys and snacks. The circus people were still angry and sad, but they also saw that Ben and Mia were sincere and kind. They accepted their apology and their help. They thanked them and gave them a hug.

Ben and Mia felt better. They learned that curiosity is good, but not when it hurts others. They learned that listening is important, especially to mom and Mia. They learned that saying sorry is good, but doing sorry is better. They learned that being kind and helpful is the best way to make friends. They learned a lot from the circus.
<|end|>


