Anna and Ben are playing in the kitchen. They have a big sink with water and many cups and spoons. They want to test which cup can hold the most water.

"I have a red cup. It is big and round. I can fill it with water," Anna says.

"I have a blue cup. It is small and square. I can fill it with water too," Ben says.

They take turns to fill their cups with water from the sink. They count how many spoons of water they can put in each cup.

"One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten. My cup is full. It can hold ten spoons of water," Anna says.

"One, two, three, four, five, six. My cup is full. It can hold six spoons of water," Ben says.

Anna and Ben look at their cups. They see that Anna's cup is bigger and can hold more water than Ben's cup.

"Anna, you win. Your cup can hold more water than my cup. You have a good cup," Ben says.

"Thank you, Ben. You have a good cup too. It is blue and square. I like blue and square. Do you want to try another cup?" Anna says.

"Yes, I do. Let's find another cup. Maybe we can find one that can hold more water than your cup," Ben says.

They put their cups on the table and look for another cup in the kitchen. They are ready to test more cups and have more fun.
