Sara likes to play with her white rabbit. She calls him Fluffy. Fluffy is soft and funny. He likes to hop and eat carrots. Sara has a cage for Fluffy. She puts him in the cage when she goes to sleep or to school.

One day, Sara's friend Lily comes to visit. Lily likes Fluffy too. She wants to play with him. Sara says, "OK, but we have to be careful. Fluffy is fast and can run away."

Sara and Lily take Fluffy out of the cage. They hold him gently and pet him. They give him some carrots and lettuce. Fluffy is happy. He wiggles his nose and ears.

But then, Fluffy sees a butterfly. He wants to chase it. He jumps out of Sara's arms and runs after the butterfly. Sara and Lily are scared. They shout, "Fluffy, come back! Fluffy, stop!"

They run after Fluffy. They try to catch him. But Fluffy is faster. He follows the butterfly to the garden. He sees some flowers. He thinks they are tasty. He nibbles on them.

Sara and Lily find Fluffy in the garden. They see him eating the flowers. They are angry. They say, "Fluffy, you are naughty! You can't eat the flowers. They are not for you. They are for Mommy. She will be mad."

They grab Fluffy and bring him back to the cage. They say, "Fluffy, you have to stay in the cage. You can't run away. You can't eat the flowers. You have to be good."

Fluffy looks at them with his big eyes. He feels sorry. He says, "Sorry, Sara. Sorry, Lily. I just wanted to have fun. I like the butterfly. I like the flowers. I didn't know they were not for me."

Sara and Lily forgive Fluffy. They say, "It's OK, Fluffy. We love you. But you have to listen to us. We know what is best for you. We want you to be safe and happy."

They hug Fluffy and give him some more carrots. Fluffy is glad. He says, "Thank you, Sara. Thank you, Lily. You are my friends. I love you too. I will be good. I will stay in the cage."

The end.
