Lily was a little girl who liked to poke things. She poked her toys, her books, her cat, and sometimes her brother. She wanted to see what would happen when she poked them. Sometimes they made noises, sometimes they moved, and sometimes they got angry.

One day, Lily saw something new in the bathroom. It was a green bottle with a spray on top. She wondered what was inside. She picked up the bottle and poked the spray. A mist came out and smelled funny. Lily coughed and sneezed. She did not like the smell.

She put the bottle down and ran out of the bathroom. She saw her mom in the kitchen. She told her mom what she did. Her mom was not happy. She told Lily that the bottle was for cleaning the bathroom, not for poking. She said that the mist was bad for Lily's nose and eyes. She took Lily to the sink and washed her face with water.

Lily felt sorry for poking the bottle. She said sorry to her mom. Her mom hugged her and said it was okay. She told Lily to be careful and not poke things that she did not know. She said that some things were not for playing, but for grown-ups. Lily nodded and said she understood. She asked her mom if she could poke her cat instead. Her mom smiled and said yes, but gently. Lily ran to find her cat and poked him softly. He purred and licked her hand. Lily was happy. She liked to poke things, but only the right things.
<|end|>


