Anna and Ben are friends who live on a farm. They like to play in the barn with the animals. One day, they find a big box in the barn. It has a label that says "mail". They are curious and want to see what is inside.

They open the box and find many toys and books. They are very happy and start to play with them. They do not think about who the box belongs to or why it is in the barn. They think it is a gift for them.

But the box is not for them. It is for Mr. Lee, the farmer who owns the barn. He ordered the box for his grandson, who is sick and lives far away. He wants to mail the box to him and make him happy. He comes to the barn to get the box, but he sees that it is open and empty. He is very sad and angry.

He asks Anna and Ben what they did with the box. They are scared and ashamed. They tell him the truth and say they are sorry. They give back the toys and books to Mr. Lee. He is still sad, but he is also fair. He tells them that they made a mistake, but they can learn from it. He says that they should not take things that are not theirs, and they should respect other people's mail. He also says that they can help him pack the box again and mail it to his grandson.

Anna and Ben feel bad for what they did, but they also feel grateful for Mr. Lee's kindness. They help him with the box and write a note to his grandson, saying that they hope he gets well soon and that they are sorry for their mistake. They also promise to be more careful and respectful in the future. They learn that mail is important and that being fair is good.
<|end|>


