Tim and Sam are friends. They like to play with cars and balls. One day, they find a big box in the park. They open the box and see many toys inside. They are very happy.

"Wow, look at all these toys!" Tim says. "Let's take some home."

"No, we can't do that," Sam says. "These toys are not ours. Maybe someone left them here by mistake. We should leave a message for them."

Sam takes a paper and a pen from his backpack. He writes on the paper: "We found your toys. We did not take any. We hope you come back soon. From Tim and Sam." He puts the paper in the box and closes it.

"Good job, Sam," Tim says. "That is very fair. Come on, let's go play with our own toys."

They walk away from the box. But they do not see a big dog behind a tree. The dog is hungry and angry. It sees the box and smells the toys. It runs to the box and bites it. It tears the paper and the toys. It makes a big mess.

The dog does not care about the message. It does not care about being fair. It only cares about biting.
