Lily was a curious girl who liked to explore new things. One day, she saw a candle on the table in the living room. She wondered what it was and how it worked. She climbed on a chair and reached for the candle.

"Be careful, Lily!" her mother said. "The candle is hot and can hurt you. It is not a toy. It is for making light when it is dark."

Lily did not listen to her mother. She wanted to touch the candle and see what it felt like. She grabbed the candle and felt a sharp pain in her hand. She dropped the candle and started to cry.

"Ow, ow, ow!" she sobbed. "It hurts, it hurts!"

Her mother ran to her and hugged her. She put some ice on her hand and kissed it gently.

"I'm sorry, Lily," her mother said. "You have a burn. It will heal soon, but it will sting for a while. You should always listen to me when I speak to you. I speak to you because I love you and I want you to be safe."

Lily nodded and hugged her mother back. She felt sorry for not obeying her mother. She learned that the candle was not a toy and that she should be careful with hot things. She also learned that her mother spoke to her for her own good and that she should respect her words. She decided to be more careful and more obedient from then on.
<|end|>


