Jill was a spoiled girl who always wanted to have the best things. She had many toys, dresses, and books, but she was not happy. She did not like to share or play with other children. She only liked to comb her long, shiny hair and look at herself in the mirror.

One day, she saw a flyer on the street that said: "Join the fun! Come to the park and make new friends! There will be games, snacks, and prizes!" Jill thought that sounded boring. She did not want to join the fun. She wanted to stay at home and comb her hair.

But her mother saw the flyer too and said: "Jill, you should go to the park and join the fun. It is good to meet other children and have fun. Maybe you will find a friend who likes to comb hair too." Jill did not want to go, but her mother made her. She put on her prettiest dress and took her favorite comb with her.

When she got to the park, she saw many children playing and laughing. They were running, jumping, sliding, and swinging. They looked happy. Jill did not want to play with them. She sat on a bench and started to comb her hair. She did not notice a boy who came near her.

The boy was curious. He saw Jill's comb and wanted to touch it. He reached out his hand and grabbed the comb. Jill was angry. She shouted: "Hey, give me back my comb! That is mine! You are a bad boy!" The boy was scared. He ran away with the comb. Jill chased him, but he was faster. He ran to the other side of the park, where there was a pond.

Jill followed him, but she did not see the pond. She was too focused on her comb. She ran and ran, until she reached the edge of the pond. She slipped and fell into the water. She got wet and dirty. She lost her comb. She cried and cried. The boy felt sorry for her. He came back and gave her the comb. He said: "I am sorry. I just wanted to see your comb. It is very pretty. Do you want to be my friend?" Jill looked at him. She looked at her comb. She looked at herself. She realized she had been very silly. She said: "Yes, I want to be your friend. Thank you for giving me back my comb. Do you want to join the fun?" The boy smiled and nodded. They held hands and went to play with the other children. Jill learned to share and have fun. She was not spoiled anymore. She was happy.
<|end|>


