Anna and Ben were best friends. They liked to play outside and look at the sky. One day, they saw a big, bright star. It was shining more than the other stars. They wanted to see it better.

"Let's go closer to the star," Anna said. "Maybe it has a wonder for us."

"OK," Ben said. "But how do we get there?"

They found a big hill near their house. They climbed up the hill. It was hard and tiring, but they did not give up. They reached the top of the hill. They looked at the star. It was very impressive.

"Wow," Anna said. "It is so beautiful. I wish we could touch it."

"Me too," Ben said. "Maybe we can fly to it. Let's jump and flap our arms."

They jumped and flapped their arms. But they did not fly. They fell down the hill. They rolled and bumped and hurt themselves. They cried and screamed. Their parents heard them and ran to help them. They took them to the doctor. The doctor gave them bandages and medicine.

"You were very foolish," the doctor said. "You cannot fly to the star. It is very far and hot. You could have burned or died. You should be happy with what you have and not chase after things you cannot reach."

Anna and Ben felt sorry and ashamed. They learned their lesson. They never tried to fly to the star again. They still liked to play outside and look at the sky, but they did not jump and flap their arms. They knew that the star was not a wonder for them, but a danger. They were more careful and grateful.
<|end|>


