Lily was a little girl who liked to draw with ink. She had many colors of ink and many papers to make pictures. She was happy when she drew.

One day, she saw a new boy in her class. His name was Tom. He looked sad and lonely. Lily wanted to be his friend. She went to him and said, "Hi, I am Lily. Do you want to draw with me? I have many colors of ink. You can use them."

Tom smiled and said, "Yes, thank you. I like to draw too. You are very nice. What is your favorite color of ink?"

Lily said, "I like pink. It is pretty. What is yours?"

Tom said, "I like black. It is cool. Can I see your pink ink?"

Lily said, "Sure, here it is. You can use it. But be careful, it can make a mess."

Tom took the pink ink and opened it. He looked at Lily and said, "I have a surprise for you. Do you want to see it?"

Lily said, "Yes, what is it?"

Tom said, "This!" And he threw the pink ink all over Lily. He laughed and said, "You look funny. You are not nice. You are silly."

Lily was shocked and sad. She was covered in pink ink. She felt wet and cold. She cried and said, "Why did you do that? That was mean. You are not my friend. You are bad."

Tom ran away and said, "I don't care. I don't like you. I don't like pink. I like black. Bye bye, pinky."

Lily was alone and hurt. She did not understand why Tom was so mean. She wanted to be his friend. She wanted to welcome him. But he did not want to be her friend. He wanted to hurt her. She did not like him. She did not like black. She did not like ink. She did not like to draw. She was unhappy.
