<|asst|>
Ben likes to balance things on his head. He thinks it is fun and funny. He can balance a book, a hat, a ball, and even a spoon. He likes to show his mom and dad how good he is at balancing.

One day, he finds a big box in the living room. It is a new television for the family. Ben wants to see what is inside the box. He opens it and sees the television. It is shiny and black and has a lot of buttons. Ben thinks it looks like a toy.

He takes the television out of the box and puts it on the floor. He tries to turn it on, but nothing happens. He thinks maybe it needs batteries. He looks for batteries in the kitchen, but he cannot find any. He sees a banana on the table. He thinks maybe the banana can make the television work. He peels the banana and puts it in the back of the television.

He goes back to the living room and tries to turn on the television again. Still nothing happens. He is disappointed. He thinks maybe the television is broken. He decides to balance it on his head instead. He lifts the television and puts it on his head. It is very heavy and hard to balance. He walks around the living room, trying to keep the television on his head.

He does not see his mom coming in the door. She sees Ben with the television on his head and the banana in the back. She is shocked and angry. She yells at Ben to put the television down. Ben is scared and loses his balance. The television falls off his head and crashes on the floor. It breaks into pieces. Ben starts to cry. His mom is very upset. She tells Ben he is in big trouble. He has to go to his room and think about what he did. He cannot play with the television anymore. He is very sorry. He wishes he did not balance the television on his head. He wishes he did not put the banana in the back. He wishes he listened to his mom and dad. He learns a hard lesson. Balancing is fun, but not with a television.
<|end|>


