Lily and Tom are friends. They like to play outside. But today it is raining. They cannot go to the park or ride their bikes. They are sad.

"Let's play a game," Lily says. "We can use our brains and have fun."

"What game?" Tom asks.

Lily thinks for a moment. She sees a big book on the shelf. It has many pictures of animals. She has an idea.

"Let's play animal sounds," she says. "I will show you a picture of an animal, and you have to make the sound it makes. If you are right, you get a point. If you are wrong, I get a point. The one with the most points wins."

"OK," Tom says. He likes animals. He thinks he is good at making sounds.

Lily opens the book and shows Tom the first picture. It is a fat pig.

"Oink, oink," Tom says.

"Good," Lily says. "You get a point."

She shows him the next picture. It is a skinny snake.

"Sssss," Tom says.

"Good," Lily says. "You get another point."

She shows him the next picture. It is a big elephant.

"Roar," Tom says.

"Wrong," Lily says. "Elephants do not roar. They trumpet. Like this." She makes a loud noise with her mouth.

"Wow," Tom says. "That is a funny sound. You get a point."

They keep playing the game. They make sounds of cows, dogs, cats, birds, and monkeys. They laugh and have fun. They forget about the rain. They use their brains and learn new things. They are happy.
<|end|>


