Lily was a lazy girl who did not like to eat vegetables. She always hid them under her plate or gave them to her dog. One day, her mom took her to the farm to see where vegetables came from.

"Look, Lily, these are carrots. They grow in the ground and they are good for your eyes," her mom said, pulling out a bright orange carrot.

Lily wrinkled her nose. "I don't like carrots. They are hard and bitter."

Her mom smiled. "Why don't you try one? Maybe you will like it if you taste it fresh from the farm."

She handed Lily a small carrot and washed it with some water. Lily hesitated, but she did not want to be rude. She took a small bite and was surprised. The carrot was sweet and crunchy. She liked it!

She realized that vegetables were not so bad after all. Maybe they tasted different when they were fresh and not cooked. She asked her mom if she could try some other vegetables, like lettuce, tomatoes, and cucumbers. Her mom was happy and agreed.

Lily ate many vegetables that day and felt good. She decided that she would not be lazy anymore and eat more vegetables at home. She also wanted to learn more about how they grew and what they did for her body. She thanked her mom for taking her to the farm and giving her a new experience. Her mom hugged her and said she was proud of her.
<|end|>


