Lily likes to number her toys. She has a lot of toys, but she knows how many she has. She counts them every day. One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten. She has ten toys.

One day, Lily finds a new toy in her room. It is a ball that makes sounds and lights. She picks it up and shakes it. It makes a funny noise and flashes red and blue. She likes it a lot. She thinks it is amazing.

She wants to number it with her other toys. She puts it on the floor and starts to count. One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten. But wait, she has one more toy now. She needs a new number. She thinks hard. What comes after ten?

She remembers what her mom told her. After ten comes eleven. She says it out loud. Eleven. She likes how it sounds. She points to the ball and says, "This is eleven." She smiles. She has learned a new number.

She decides to play with the ball. She rolls it on the floor and watches it make sounds and lights. She sees it change its motion. Sometimes it goes fast, sometimes it goes slow. Sometimes it bounces, sometimes it stops. She laughs and claps. She thinks it is the best toy ever. She is happy. She has a new toy and a new number.
