<|asst|>
Lily liked to tie her hair with ribbons. She had many ribbons of different colors and patterns. She thought they made her look cute and happy. She also liked to learn new languages. She had a book with pictures and words from many places. She wanted to talk to people from all over the world.

One day, she went to the park with her mom and dad. She saw a girl playing with a ball. The girl had long hair and a ribbon like Lily. Lily wanted to be friends with her. She ran to the girl and said hello. The girl looked at Lily and said something. Lily did not understand. It was a different language. Lily tried to say something from her book. The girl laughed and said something else. Lily felt sad and confused.

She ran back to her mom and dad. She told them what happened. They hugged her and said they were sorry. They said that not everyone was nice and that some people did not like other languages. They said that Lily should be proud of her ribbons and her book. They said that they loved her very much.

Lily smiled and said she loved them too. She felt better. She decided to keep tying her hair with ribbons and learning new languages. She hoped to find a friend who liked them too.

But she never did. The other kids at the park, at school, and at home made fun of her. They called her names and pulled her ribbons. They said that her languages were weird and silly. They said that she was not cute and happy, but strange and stupid. Lily cried and cried. She stopped tying her hair with ribbons and learning new languages. She threw away her book and her ribbons. She tried to be like the other kids. But they still did not like her. They still laughed and said mean things. Lily felt alone and unhappy. She wished she had never gone to the park that day. She wished she had never met that girl with the ball. She wished she had never said hello.
<|end|>


