<|asst|>
Sara liked to act. She liked to pretend she was a princess, a fairy, a doctor, or anything she wanted. She had many toys and costumes to help her act. But her favorite toy was her flute. She loved to play her flute and make music. She felt happy and free when she played her flute.

One day, Sara went to the park with her mom and her flute. She saw some other kids playing on the swings, the slide, and the sandbox. She wanted to join them and make friends. She thought they would like her flute and her acting. She walked up to them and said hello. She showed them her flute and asked if they wanted to hear her play.

But the other kids did not want to hear her play. They laughed at her flute and said it was silly and boring. They said they did not like acting and that she was weird. They told her to go away and leave them alone. Sara felt sad and hurt. She did not understand why they were so mean to her. She ran back to her mom and cried.

Her mom hugged her and wiped her tears. She told her that some kids can be mean and rude, but that does not mean she should stop playing her flute and acting. She told her that her flute and her acting were special and beautiful, and that she should be proud of them. She told her that she was a humble and kind girl, and that those are the best qualities to have. She told her that she would always love her and support her.

Sara felt better and smiled. She thanked her mom and gave her a kiss. She decided to ignore the mean kids and keep playing her flute and acting. She knew that her mom was right, and that she was humble and kind. She also knew that someday, she would find other kids who would appreciate her flute and her acting, and who would be her true friends. She played her flute and acted happily, and felt happy and free again.
<|end|>


